  <generalInformation><![CDATA[<h3>Beginner skiing and snowboarding in Arabba </h3>
<p>Arabba has some decent nursey slopes but no obvious easy greens or blues to progress to. Beginners would be best suited heading over to <a data-udi="umb://document/f5a15898b6694ef6a1c755346a0e1ba8" href="/{localLink:umb://document/f5a15898b6694ef6a1c755346a0e1ba8}" title="Corvara &amp; Colfosco">Corvara or Colfosco</a>.</p>
<h3>Intermediate skiing and snowboarding in Arabba</h3>
<p>Intermediates are in for an absolute treat when visiting Arabba. Here you'll find varied slopes with mainly blue and red runs on the Porta Vescovo and the Passo Pordoi. Beyond Arabba’s main ski area, the Sella Ronda and the Alta Badia areas provide extensive skiing, so you'll have lots of runs to choose from and plenty of opportunity to get some miles under your belt. </p>
<h3>Advanced skiing and snowboarding in Arabba</h3>
<p>Arabba is one of the best resorts in the Dolomiti Superski area for advanced skiers and boarders. Here you will find exhilarating black ski runs from the scenic Porta Vescovo mountain, which reach 2,500 metres, a real challenge as well as the testing skiing on the famous Marmolada Glacier.</p>
<h3>Off piste and snow parks in Arabba</h3>
<p>There is also some interesting off-piste dotted around the resort area that can easily be accessed with a guide. </p>
<p>While there is no snow park in Arabba, just head toward Alta Badia where you can hit up the jumps and rails. </p>
<p> </p>]]></generalInformation>
